  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most common mistakes sellers make is applying a fixed strategy regardless of market conditions. An approach that produces a strong result in a seller's market, with multiple bidders competing at auction, can produce a poor one when buyer sentiment has shifted and stock is building. The mechanics of pricing, campaign method, and negotiation all need to adjust to the conditions you are actually selling into, not the conditions you would prefer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to read the current market</h2>
      <p>Before discussing strategy, you need to understand the state of the market in your suburb and price range. The indicators that matter most are:</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Auction clearance rate.</strong> A rate consistently above 65% signals strong buyer competition and a market tilting in the seller's favour. Below 55%, buyers have more leverage. Below 50%, conditions have shifted meaningfully toward buyers.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Days on market.</strong> If comparable properties are selling within two to three weeks, demand is strong. If similar homes are sitting for six to eight weeks or longer, buyers are taking their time and negotiating harder. A rising median days on market across consecutive months is one of the clearest indicators of a softening trend.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Active stock levels.</strong> How many comparable properties are currently listed and competing with yours? In a rising market, stock is absorbed quickly and the number of active listings stays low. In a softening market, unsold inventory accumulates and buyers gain choice.</p>

      <p>These three indicators together give you a reliable read on where the market sits before you commit to a strategy.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Selling in a rising market</h2>
      <p>When clearance rates are elevated, days on market is short, and active stock is low, buyer competition is doing a significant amount of work for you. The strategy in this environment is to channel that competition effectively rather than trying to extract maximum price through a fixed asking price.</p>

      <p>Auction is generally the preferred campaign method in a rising market. A competitive auction environment, with multiple registered bidders, consistently outperforms private treaty in conditions where buyers are willing to push each other upward. The key discipline is setting a realistic reserve: a figure that reflects current comparable sales, not an aspirational number that risks the property passing in and losing momentum.</p>

      <p>Overpricing is one of the few reliable ways to destroy a strong result in a rising market. A property that is significantly overquoted will deter early inspections, reduce the number of buyers who register to bid, and can cause a well-prepared campaign to stall just when the market is working in your favour. In a rising market, a price guide that attracts strong attendance and generates competition will almost always produce a better result than an ambitious asking price that limits your buyer pool.</p>

      <p>Timing has less urgency in a rising market. Motivated sellers can achieve strong results year-round because demand is broad and the window of opportunity is extended.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Selling in a stable or moderately softening market</h2>
      <p>When the market is moving sideways or showing early signs of easing, buyer competition has reduced. Clearance rates are coming off their highs, days on market is creeping up, and buyers are doing more due diligence before committing. The strategy needs to adapt.</p>

      <p>Pricing correctly from day one becomes critical. In a rising market, an overpriced property often sells anyway because demand eventually catches up. In a softening market, it does not. A property that launches at a price buyers consider too high will sit, accumulate days on market, and require a price reduction that signals weakness. The first two weeks of any campaign are the most important: this is when the broadest pool of active buyers is paying attention, and a stale listing at the wrong price will be skipped by exactly the buyers you need.</p>

      <p>Private treaty with genuine flexibility on terms can outperform auction in this environment. Buyers who are less willing to compete under auction conditions will often engage substantively under private treaty if the price is sensible and the terms allow them adequate time for finance and due diligence. Long settlement terms, flexibility on inclusions, and a vendor who responds quickly to offers can make the difference between a conditional offer converting and falling over.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Selling in a falling market</h2>
      <p>In a genuinely falling market, buyer sentiment is cautious, finance conditions are tighter, inspections are down, and the number of buyers who make offers as a proportion of those who attend is lower. The strategy in this environment is straightforwardly different from either of the above.</p>

      <p>The priority shifts from maximising price to minimising days on market. In a falling market, a property that is still available in six weeks is not just unsold: it is worth less than it was when it launched, because the market has moved further downward while the listing has been accumulating days on market. A quick, unconditional sale at a price that reflects current market reality is a better outcome than a protracted campaign chasing a number that is receding.</p>

      <p>Pricing aggressively, meaning pricing to be the most competitive listing in your suburb among genuinely comparable properties, is the most reliable approach. Buyers in a falling market have options and are watching closely. A property that is clearly priced below its competitors will generate inspections and offers. A property priced at the top of the range, even with a premium presentation, will sit.</p>

      <p>In a falling market, vendor expectations are the most common source of poor outcomes. Sellers who have anchored to prices achieved by neighbours twelve months earlier, when conditions were different, are often the last to adjust and consequently the ones who achieve the worst results relative to where they could have sold had they moved quickly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The principle that applies in every market</h2>
      <p>Across all three conditions, one principle holds: properties that are priced correctly sell. What changes between a rising market and a falling one is what correctly priced looks like. In a rising market, correctly priced means setting a guide that generates competition and allows the auction process to discover the true ceiling. In a falling market, correctly priced means meeting the market where it actually is, not where you would prefer it to be.</p>

      <p>The sellers who navigate a falling market well are not lucky. They are the ones who accept early that the market has changed, adjust their expectations ahead of the data forcing them to, and execute a clean, well-priced campaign before their competitors do the same thing.</p>

